    <text>
        <body>
            <head>240. Memorandum From the Executive Secretary of the Department of State (<persName
                    corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">Tarnoff</persName>) to the President’s Assistant for
                National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu"
                    >Brzezinski</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d240fn1"
                    >Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material,
                    Brzezinski Office File, Country Chron File, Box 33, Morocco: 1979. Confidential.
                    There is no indication <persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu"
                        >Brzezinski</persName> saw the memorandum.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1979-08-15"
                        >August 15, 1979</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Proposed Presidential Message to King <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh"
                        >Hassan</persName> of <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                        >Morocco</placeName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>Events in the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">western Sahara</placeName> are
                moving rapidly following <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi"
                    >Mauritania</placeName>’s separate peace with the <orgName
                    corresp="recejMOrt8OMiixBL">Polisario</orgName>. The <orgName
                    corresp="recejMOrt8OMiixBL">Polisario</orgName> has mounted a major attack on a
                Moroccan position at the southern end of the Moroccan portion of the <placeName
                    corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">western Sahara</placeName>. <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> appears to be in the process of
                claiming the former Mauritanian portion of the western Sahara.<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d240fn2">
                    <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi">Mauritania</placeName> and the <orgName
                        corresp="recejMOrt8OMiixBL">Polisario</orgName> concluded a peace agreement
                    on August 5. <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi">Mauritania</placeName>
                    renounced all territorial claims to the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK"
                        >Western Sahara</placeName>. In an August 17 memorandum to <persName
                        corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="rec9EBLnqQPcxRtYr">Christopher</persName> wrote: “<placeName
                        corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> has ‛incorporated’ the
                    former Mauritanian portion of the <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western
                        Sahara</placeName> into <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                        >Morocco</placeName> as its 37th province. Although <placeName
                        corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> has denounced this Moroccan
                    takeover as ‛aggression,’ it will not ask for a <orgName
                        corresp="recI8JFNFTJYHnXbK">
                        <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> Security Council</orgName> meeting at
                    this time. The <orgName corresp="recejMOrt8OMiixBL">Polisario</orgName> have
                    vowed to continue their attacks in <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                        >Morocco</placeName> proper.” (Carter Library, National Security Affairs,
                    Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 22, Evening Reports (State): 8/79)</note>
                While such a move might temporarily reduce pressure in <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> to attack <orgName
                    corresp="recejMOrt8OMiixBL">Polisario</orgName> bases in <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName>, the <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recD8UEyBEWnzRQtf">situation</rs> is unsettled and fighting could
                escalate rapidly. We recommend that the President send a friendly message to King
                    <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh">Hassan</persName> acknowledging the
                problems he is facing and reiterating our interest in a peaceful solution. A
                proposed message is attached.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d240fn3">The undated
                    message is attached but not printed. In part, the message reads: “I want you to
                    know that I have been deeply distressed by the attacks on your forces well
                    inside <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>. I sympathize
                    with you in this situation, and recognize that there have been other recent
                    developments which have serious implications for <placeName
                        corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> and the region. All of us
                    must do our best to ensure that these developments will not lead to further
                    widening of the conflict. In this regard, I am uneasy about the possible
                    repercussions of the reported new Moroccan moves in the Tiris
                    al-Gharbia.”</note>
            </p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Peter Tarnoff</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Executive Secretary</hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
